            <div type="note">
                <head type="title">George Gordon, Lord Byron (<date notBefore="1788" notAfter="1824">1788&#x2013;1824</date>)</head>
                <p>In <date when="1834-01">January 1834</date>, when <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>&#x02BC;s <persName corresp="#JJR">father</persName> wrote in reply to 
                    <ref type="note" subtype="biographical" target="hogg_james_note.html"><persName corresp="#JH">James Hogg</persName> (ca. <date notBefore="1770" notAfter="1835">1770&#x2013;1835</date>)</ref>, 
                    who had asked for an account of <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>&#x02BC;s progress in using his wonderful abilities, <persName corresp="JJR">John James</persName> included a sample of <persName corresp="#JR">John</persName>&#x02BC;s rhymes, possibly taken from 
                    <ref type="apparatus" target="account_of_a_tour_on_the_continent_apparatus.html">Account of a Tour on the Continent</ref>, which <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> was composing at that time. 
                    <persName corresp="#JH">Hogg</persName>&#x02BC;s critique of the lines, which is known only from <persName corresp="JR">Ruskin</persName>&#x02BC;s reply to <persName corresp="#JH">Hogg</persName>, dwelled on the boy&#x02BC;s imitation of <persName corresp="#WS">Scott</persName> and <persName corresp="#GGB">Byron</persName>, 
                    presumably intending to encourage greater originality. 
                    <persName corresp="JR">Ruskin</persName>&#x02BC;s comment identifies the boy&#x02BC;s sense of how these two poets related to one another: 
                    &#x201C;I have read <persName corresp="#GGB">Byron</persName> with wonder, and <persName corresp="#WS">Scott</persName> with delight, they have caused me many a day-dream and night-dream&#x201D; 
                    (<ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.html#GARDENMEMORIALS">Garden, ed., <title type="book" corresp="#GARDENMEMORIALS"><hi rend="italic">Memorials of James Hogg</hi></title></ref>, 277).
                </p>
            </div>
